-- 
South African Stocks Advance: Merafe Slides to Lowest Since December 2009

-- B y   S t e p h e n   G u n n i o n
-- 
2011-07-20T16:44:30Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-07-20/south-african-stocks-advance-merafe-slides-to-lowest-since-december-2009.html
The FTSE/JSE  Africa  All Share Index
fell for the first day in two, easing 2.62, or less than 0.1
percent, to 32,056.06 by the 5 p.m. close in Johannesburg.  The following are among the most active stocks in the South
African market today.  Anglo American Plc (AGL)  , the diversified mining company
that makes up 10 percent of the benchmark  stock index , dropped
2.20 rand, or 0.7 percent, to 330 rand. De Beers, in which Anglo
has a 45 percent stake, is facing a strike over pay at its
operations in  South Africa  from July 22 after talks with the
National Union of Mineworkers failed to secure an agreement, the
labor union said in an e-mailed statement today.  AngloGold Ashanti Ltd. (ANG)  , Africa’s largest gold
producer, fell 7.54 rand, or 2.4 percent, to 305.22 rand, a
second day of declines. Gold retreated from a record high,
falling as much as 0.5 percent to $1,581.34 an ounce.  Gold Fields Ltd. (GFI)  , Africa’s second-biggest producer
of the metal, fell for a second day, declining 81 cents, or 0.8
percent, to 107.49 rand.  DRDGold Ltd. (DRD)  , South Africa’s fourth-largest
producer of the metal, fell for the first day in three, dropping
5 cents, or 1.5 percent, to 3.24 rand.  BHP Billiton Plc (BIL)  , the world’s biggest mining
group, rose for a second day, gaining 1.34 rand, or 0.5 percent,
to 262.72 rand. The group reported annual production records
across four commodities and ten operations as prices for  iron
ore , coal and copper reached records.  FirstRand Ltd. (FSR)  , South Africa’s second-largest
banking group, gained for a second day, adding 11 cents, or 0.6
percent, to 19.71 rand. The group’s Indian operation has made a
profit a year earlier than the lender expected it to, Business
Day reported, citing Chief Executive Officer Sizwe Nxasana.  Massmart Holdings Ltd. (MSM)  , the South African retailer
controlled by Wal-Mart Stores Inc., rose for the first day in
four, adding 1.86 rand, or 1.3 percent, to 144.60 rand. The
retailer plans to open about 75 Cambridge food stores in the
next five years and may also add about five or six Macro stores
and 10 to 15 Builders Warehouse units, Chief Executive Officer
Grant Pattison told reporters in Cape Town today.  Merafe Resources Ltd. (MRF)  , a ferrochrome mining
company, closed at its lowest in two years, dropping 3 cents, or
2.6 percent, to 1.11 rand. Earnings per share for the six months
to June 30 are expected to decline to between 3 cents and 4
cents from 8 cents a year earlier, the group said in a trading
statement.  Sappi Ltd. (SAP)  , the world’s biggest maker of glossy
paper, closed at its lowest in more than a year, declining 57
cents, or 1.8 percent, to 31.75 rand. The company opted to close
its Biberist mill in  Switzerland  after failing to find a buyer
for the operation.  South Ocean Holdings Ltd. (SOH)  , a maker of power
cables, ended at its weakest in more than a year, declining 4
cents, or 2.4 percent, to 1.61 rand. The company said in a
trading statement that headline earnings per share and earnings
per share for the six months to June 30 were expected to be 25
percent to 35 percent lower than the corresponding prior period.  To contact the reporter on this story:
